Final Assignment:¶

The aim of this project is to investigate the Following research questions:¶

1- Is there any difference in the mean BMI values between males and females?¶
2- Is there any difference in the mean BMI values between the two types of gender seperation?¶
3- Assess the effect of BMI on Glucose and Cholestrol separately?¶

The data is collected from the Lifeline dataset including; "continious" and "complete". The "continious" data set referes to the case in which a person has been participated in both data collection times. While, the "complete" data set referes to the case in which a person has participated in one or both data collection times. In this study the continious data is considered. For more information please read the "Toolkit - Aletta Year Challenge 2022" pdf file.

The following steps are required to answer the above research questions:

part 1: Load and Clean the data

part 2: Merge the Dataframes

part 3: Data Visualization (map, bar plots, scatter plot, correlation and heat map)

part 4: Statistical Analysis (Question1 (2-sample ttest), Question2 (2-sample ttest), Question3 (ANOVA))

part 5: Deduction

def seperate_columns(df):

    df = df.columns.to_frame().T.append(df, ignore_index=True) #convert header to row
    df.columns = range(len(df.columns)) #number the column
    df = df[0].str.split('\t', expand=True) #split columns
    df.columns = df.iloc[0] # consider the first row as header
    df = df[1:] #eliminate first row which was the copy of header
    
    return df

Which data is required:¶

ZIPCODE: Postal code 4 Baseline visit 1

GENDER: Gender (1=male, 2=female)

GENDER_MALE: Male participants in percentage

GENDER_FEMALE: Female participants in percentage

BMI_T1:Body Mass Index (kg/M^2) at baseline as mean (T1)

BMI_T2:Body Mass Index (kg/M^2) at baseline as mean (T2)

CHO_T1:Cholesterol (mmol/L) assessed on samples from baseline as mean (T1)

CHO_T2:Cholesterol (mmol/L) assessed on samples from second assessment second visit as mean (T2)

GLU_T1:Glucose (mmol/L) assessed on samples from baseline as mean (T1)

GLU_T2:Glucose (mmol/L) assessed on samples from second assessment secondvisit as mean (T2)

def rename_columns(df = new_df):
    '''
    This function renames the name of columns
    parameter: new_df
    return: renamed new_df
    
    '''
    df.rename(columns={
        'BMI_T1_x': 'BMI_T1_sex_%',
        'BMI_T2_x': 'BMI_T2_sex_%',
        'BMI_T1_y': 'BMI_T1_sex_code',
        'BMI_T2_y': 'BMI_T2_sex_code',

        'GLU_T1_x': 'Glucose_T1_sex_%',
        'GLU_T2_x': 'Glucose_T2_sex_%',
        'GLU_T1_y': 'Glucose_T1_sex_code',
        'GLU_T2_y': 'Glucose_T2_sex_code',

        'CHO_T1_x': 'Cholestrol_T1_sex_%',
        'CHO_T2_x': 'Cholestrol_T2_sex_%',
        'CHO_T1_y': 'Cholestrol_T1_sex_code',
        'CHO_T2_y': 'Cholestrol_T2_sex_code'
        }, inplace=True)
    return df

# bar plot:
def bar_plot_mean(df = new_df):
    '''
    This function calculate the mean of BMI, Cholestrol, and Glucose.
    Then returns Bar plot of means.
    parameter: new_df
    return: bar plot of mean
    '''

    Times = ['First data collection time', 'Second data collection time']
    factors = ['BMI(kg/M^2)', 'Glucose((mmol/L)', 'Cholesterol((mmol/L)']
    BMI =list(); CHO = list(); GLU = list() 
    BMI.append((new_df[ 'BMI_T1_sex_code'].mean()+ new_df[ 'BMI_T1_sex_%'].mean())/2)
    BMI.append((new_df['BMI_T2_sex_code'].mean()+ new_df[ 'BMI_T2_sex_%'].mean())/2)

    CHO.append((new_df[ 'Cholestrol_T1_sex_code'].mean()+ new_df[ 'Cholestrol_T1_sex_%'].mean())/2)
    CHO.append((new_df[ 'Cholestrol_T2_sex_code'].mean()+ new_df[ 'Cholestrol_T2_sex_%'].mean())/2)

    GLU.append((new_df['Glucose_T1_sex_code'].mean()+ new_df['Glucose_T1_sex_%'].mean())/2)
    GLU.append((new_df[ 'Glucose_T2_sex_code'].mean()+ new_df['Glucose_T2_sex_%'].mean())/2)

    data = {'Time' : Times,
            'BMI'   : BMI,
            'Glucose'   : GLU,
            'Cholesterol'   : CHO}

    palette = ["#c9d9d3", "#718dbf", "#e84d60"]

    # this creates [ ("BMI", "T1"), ("BMI", "T2"), ("Glucose", "T1"), ("Glucose", "T2"), ... ]
    x = [ (time, factor) for time in Times for factor in factors ]
    counts = sum(zip(data['BMI'], data['Glucose'], data['Cholesterol']), ()) # like an hstack

    source = ColumnDataSource(data=dict(x=x, counts=counts))

    p = figure(x_range=FactorRange(*x), height=400, width=900,
               title="Mean of BMI, Glucose, and Cholesterol in both data collection times",
               y_axis_label="Mean",
               toolbar_location=None, tools="")

    p.vbar(x='x', top='counts', width=0.9, source=source, line_color="white",
           fill_color=factor_cmap('x', palette=palette, factors=factors, start=1, end=2))

    p.y_range.start = 0
    p.x_range.range_padding = 0.1
    p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 1
    p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None

    return p

show(bar_plot_mean(df = new_df))

# scatter plot

def scatter_plot(time = 'time 1', gender_seperation ='percentage'):
    '''
    This function returns scatter plot based on BMI,Glucose, and Cholestrol.
    There is two data collection times, and two data collection ways.
    parameters: time: time1,time2
                gender seperation: percentage,code
    return: scatter plot
    '''

    if time =='time 1' and gender_seperation =='percentage':
        x = np.array(new_df['BMI_T1_sex_%'])
        y1 = np.array(new_df['Glucose_T1_sex_%'])
        y2 = np.array(new_df['Cholestrol_T1_sex_%'])
    if time =='time 1' and gender_seperation =='code':
        x = np.array(new_df[ 'BMI_T1_sex_code'])
        y1 = np.array(new_df['Glucose_T1_sex_code'])
        y2 = np.array(new_df['Cholestrol_T1_sex_code'])
        
    if time =='time 2' and gender_seperation =='percentage':
        x = np.array(new_df[ 'BMI_T2_sex_%'])
        y1 = np.array(new_df[ 'Glucose_T2_sex_%'])
        y2 = np.array(new_df['Cholestrol_T2_sex_%'])
        
    if time =='time 2' and gender_seperation =='code':
        x = np.array(new_df[ 'BMI_T2_sex_code'])
        y1 = np.array(new_df[ 'Glucose_T2_sex_code'])
        y2 = np.array(new_df[ 'Cholestrol_T2_sex_code'])
    
    
    # Regression model of each pair (BMI/Glucose and BMI/Cholesterol)
    # Make and fit a linear regression model
    model1 = LinearRegression().fit(x.reshape(-1, 1), y1)
    model2 = LinearRegression().fit(x.reshape(-1, 1), y2)
    # x values need to be in a two-dimensional array, so use .reshape(-1, 1)
    
    # Find the slope and intercept from the model
    slope1 = model1.coef_[0] # Takes the first element of the array
    slope2 = model2.coef_[0]
    
    intercept1 = model1.intercept_
    intercept2 = model2.intercept_
    
    # Make the regression line
    regression_line1 = Slope(gradient=slope1, y_intercept=intercept1, line_color="red", line_width=2)
    regression_line2 = Slope(gradient=slope2, y_intercept=intercept2, line_color="Blue", line_width=2)
    
    
    p = figure(title = 'Glucose and Cholesterol over BMI in '+ time,
               x_axis_label = 'BMI(kg/M^2)',y_axis_label = 'Glucose/Cholesterol ((mmol/L)',
               background_fill_color="white", height=500, width=900)
    
    p.circle(x,y1,color = 'red', size=8, legend_label = 'Glucose')
    p.circle(x,y2,color = 'blue', size=8, legend_label = 'Cholesterol')
    
    p.add_layout(regression_line1)
    p.add_layout(regression_line2)
            
    return p

    This function has dataframes and by means of seaborn gallery shown heat maps

    correlation = df.corr()
    
    # plot heatmap by seaborn gallery
    plt.title('Percentage of Correlation, gender separation by '+ gender_seperation , fontsize=18)
    sns.heatmap(correlation, annot = True, cmap=cmap, vmin=0, vmax=1)
    plt.show()

At first BMI values should be categorized. After that, to check the Normality, the Shapiro-Wilk normality test should be used.

def categorical_BMI(df = new_df.copy()):
    '''
    This function classified BMI based on the following:
    18.5 to 25: Normal weight
    25 to 27: Slightly overweight
    27 to 30: Moderately overweight
    parameter: dataframe
    return: dataframe contained categorized BMI
    '''
    
    BMI_list = ['BMI_T1_sex_%','BMI_T1_sex_code','BMI_T2_sex_%','BMI_T2_sex_code']
    for i in BMI_list:

        normal = np.array(df[df[i].between(18,25)][i])
        s_overweight = np.array(df[df[i].between(25, 27)][i])
        m_overweight = np.array(df[df[i].between(27, 30)][i])

        df[i] = df[i].replace (normal, 'Normal weight')
        df[i] = df[i].replace (s_overweight, 'Slightly overweight')
        df[i] = df[i].replace (m_overweight, 'Moderately overweight')

    return df

categorical_df = categorical_BMI(df = new_df.copy())

def shapiro_wilk(df = new_df.copy()):
    '''
    This function test Normality of the data by shapiro_wilk test.
    parameters: df = new_df
    returns: two lists: one for normal data, the other for not normal data
    '''
    
    BMI_GLU_CHO_list = [['Glucose_T1_sex_%','BMI_T1_sex_%'],['Glucose_T2_sex_%','BMI_T2_sex_%'],
                   ['Glucose_T1_sex_code','BMI_T1_sex_code'],['Glucose_T2_sex_code','BMI_T2_sex_code'],
                   ['Cholestrol_T1_sex_%','BMI_T1_sex_%'],['Cholestrol_T2_sex_%','BMI_T2_sex_%'],
                   ['Cholestrol_T1_sex_code','BMI_T1_sex_code'],['Cholestrol_T2_sex_code','BMI_T2_sex_code']]
    BMI_kinds = ['Normal weight','Slightly overweight','Moderately overweight']
    normal =[]
    not_normal =[]
    for i, j in BMI_GLU_CHO_list:
        for k in BMI_kinds:
            statistic, pvalue = shapiro(categorical_df[categorical_df[j] == k][i])
            print (i,'_',j,'In BMI category of',k, 'P_value: ',pvalue)
            if pvalue<0.05:
                print ('pvalue is less than 0.05, so the data tested are NOT normally distributed\n')
                not_normal.append([i,j,k])
            if pvalue>0.05:
                print ('pvalue is greater than 0.05, so the data tested ARE normally distributed\n')
                normal.append([i,j,k])
    return normal,not_normal
normal, not_normal = shapiro_wilk(df = new_df.copy())

4-3-2: Test of Homogeneity of Variance:¶

The equality of variance in all groups should be assessed by Levene or Bartlett test. Leven test is used for non_normal data, and Bartlett test is used for normal data. Since we have both Normal and non_normal data, both Bartlett and Leven tests need to be used to test the homogeneity of variance.

In [34]:
def Homogeneity_bartlett_test():
    '''
    This function tests the equality of variances in all groups.
    If the Bartlett test shows p_values greater than 0.05, so the variances are equal,
    else they are not equal.
    '''
    for i, j, k in normal:
        statistic, pvalue = stats.bartlett(categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Normal weight'],
                     categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Slightly overweight'],
                     categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Moderately overweight'])
        print (i,'_',j,'In BMI category of',k, 'P_value: ',pvalue)
        if pvalue<0.05:
            print ('pvalue is less than 0.05, so all groups have NOT equal variance\n')
        if pvalue>0.05:
            print ('pvalue is greater than 0.05, so all groups HAVE equal variance\n')

def Homogeneity_levene_test():
    '''
    This function tests the equality of variances in all groups.
    If the Levene test shows p_values greater than 0.05, so the variances are equal,
    else they are not equal.
    '''
    for i, j, k in not_normal:
        statistic, pvalue = stats.levene(categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Normal weight'],
                     categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Slightly overweight'],
                     categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Moderately overweight'])
        print (i,'_',j,'In BMI category of',k, 'P_value: ',pvalue)
        if pvalue<0.05:
            print ('pvalue is less than 0.05, so all groups have NOT equal variance\n')
        if pvalue>0.05:
            print ('pvalue is greater than 0.05, so all groups HAVE equal variance\n')

4-3-3: ANOVA:¶

The assumptions of testing ANOVA are checked (Normality, Homogeneity test).

ANOVA test can be checked for the effects of BMI on Glucose which have equal variance.

In terms of BMI effects on cholestrol, which have not equal variance, the Kruskal-Wallis test should be used.(Kruskal-Wallis test is the non-parametric version of the one-way ANOVA)

In [37]:
def One_way_ANOVA():
    
    BMI_GLU_list = [['Glucose_T1_sex_%','BMI_T1_sex_%'],['Glucose_T2_sex_%','BMI_T2_sex_%'],
                    ['Glucose_T1_sex_code','BMI_T1_sex_code'],['Glucose_T2_sex_code','BMI_T2_sex_code']]

    for i, j in BMI_GLU_list:
            statistic, pvalue = stats.f_oneway (categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Normal weight'],
                         categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Slightly overweight'],
                         categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Moderately overweight'])
            print (i,'_',j, ', P_value: ',pvalue)
            if pvalue<0.05:
                print ('pvalue is less than 0.05. There IS a statistically significant difference between the groups and their effects the Glucose \n')
            if pvalue>0.05:
                print ('pvalue is greater than 0.05. There is NOT a statistically significant difference between the groups and their effects the Glucose\n')
            
One_way_ANOVA()

def Kruskal_Wallis():
    
    BMI_CHO_list = [['Cholestrol_T1_sex_%','BMI_T1_sex_%'],['Cholestrol_T2_sex_%','BMI_T2_sex_%'],
                    ['Cholestrol_T1_sex_code','BMI_T1_sex_code'],['Cholestrol_T2_sex_code','BMI_T2_sex_code']]

    for i, j in BMI_CHO_list:
            statistic, pvalue = stats.kruskal (categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Normal weight'],
                         categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Slightly overweight'],
                         categorical_df[i][categorical_df[j] == 'Moderately overweight'])
            print (i,'_',j, ', P_value: ',pvalue)
            if pvalue<0.05:
                print ('pvalue is less than 0.05. There IS a statistically significant difference between the groups and their effects the Cholestrol \n')
            if pvalue>0.05:
                print ('pvalue is greater than 0.05. There is NOT a statistically significant difference between the groups and their effects the Cholestrol\n')

Part 5: Deduction:¶

In this research, three research questions have been investigated:

1- Is there any difference in the mean BMI values between males and females?¶

ans:¶

To seperate BMI values based on male and female, .groupby('GENDER') is used, Normality checked, and finally 2-sample t_test is used. As a conclusion, There IS a significant difference in mean BMI values between males and females.

2- Is there any difference in the mean BMI values between the two types of gender seperation?¶

ans:¶

Based on the Normality check outcome and 2-sample t_test results; there is NO significant difference of mean BMI values between two gender seperation methods observed.

3- Assess the effect of BMI on Glucose and Cholestrol separately?¶

ans:¶

To answer this question, ANOVA method with the assumptions of Normality and Homogeneity is used. The ANOVA test is used for equal variance(BMI and Glucose), whereas the Kruskal_Wallis test is used for not equal variance(BMI and Cholestrol).

Based on ANOVA and Kruskal_Wallis test, there IS a statistically significant difference between the groups of BMI and their effects the Glucose and Cholestrol. So, BMI has influence on Cholestrol and Glucose.
